# CSV Parser - Quick Start Guide

## Installation

Copy `csv-parser.ts` or `csv-parser.js` to your project.

```typescript
// TypeScript
import { parseCSV } from './csv-parser';

// JavaScript  
const { parseCSV } = require('./csv-parser');
```

## Basic Usage - 30 Seconds

```javascript
const csv = `name,age,city
John,30,New York
Jane,25,Los Angeles`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.log(result.rows);     // Array of objects
console.log(result.headers);  // ['name', 'age', 'city']
console.log(result.errors);   // Any parsing errors
```

## Common Operations

### Parse CSV String
```javascript
const result = parseCSV(csvString);
```

### Access Data
```javascript
result.rows[0].name        // Get field value
result.headers             // Get column names
result.count()             // Total rows
```

### Filter Rows
```javascript
const adults = result.filter(row => row.age >= 18);
const engineers = result.filter(row => row.department === 'Engineering');
```

### Calculate Sums
```javascript
const totalSalary = result.sum('salary');
const totalCost = result.sum('price');
```

### Calculate Averages
```javascript
const avgAge = result.average('age');
const avgScore = result.average('test_score');
```

### Group Data
```javascript
const byDepartment = result.groupBy('department');
// Map { 'Engineering': [...], 'Marketing': [...], ... }

byDepartment.forEach((rows, dept) => {
  console.log(`${dept}: ${rows.length} employees`);
});
```

## Custom Options

### Different Delimiter
```javascript
// Semicolon
parseCSV(csv, { delimiter: ';' })

// Pipe
parseCSV(csv, { delimiter: '|' })

// Tab
parseCSV(csv, { delimiter: '\t' })
```

### All Options
```javascript
parseCSV(csv, {
  delimiter: ',',        // Field separator
  quoteChar: '"',        // Quote character
  lineSeparator: '\n'    // Line separator
})
```

## Type Handling

Automatic detection:

```javascript
// Numbers
'123'      → 123 (number)
'95.5'     → 95.5 (number)
'1e5'      → 100000 (number)

// Booleans
'true'     → true (boolean)
'false'    → false (boolean)
'TRUE'     → true (boolean)

// Nulls
'null'     → null
'NULL'     → null
''         → null

// Strings
'hello'    → 'hello' (string)
'New York' → 'New York' (string)
```

## Handle Errors

```javascript
const result = parseCSV(csv);

if (result.errors.length > 0) {
  result.errors.forEach(err => {
    console.error(`Row ${err.row}: ${err.message}`);
  });
}

// Valid rows are still parsed
console.log(`Parsed ${result.rows.length} valid rows`);
```

## Real-World Examples

### Sales Analysis
```javascript
const sales = parseCSV(salesCSV);

// Total revenue
const revenue = sales.sum('amount');

// By salesperson
const byPerson = sales.groupBy('salesperson');
byPerson.forEach((rows, person) => {
  const total = rows.reduce((s, r) => s + r.amount, 0);
  console.log(`${person}: $${total}`);
});
```

### Student Grades
```javascript
const grades = parseCSV(gradesCSV);

// Average grade
const avg = grades.average('score');

// By class
const byClass = grades.groupBy('class_id');

// Top students
const top = grades.filter(g => g.score >= 90);
```

### Employee Data
```javascript
const employees = parseCSV(empCSV);

// High earners
const highEarners = employees.filter(e => e.salary > 100000);

// By department
const byDept = employees.groupBy('department');
byDept.forEach((emps, dept) => {
  const count = emps.length;
  const avgSalary = emps.reduce((s, e) => s + e.salary, 0) / count;
  console.log(`${dept}: ${count} people, $${avgSalary} avg`);
});
```

## Special Cases

### Quoted Fields with Commas
```csv
name,address
John,"123 Main St, Suite 100"
```
✓ Correctly handles: "123 Main St, Suite 100"

### Escaped Quotes
```csv
name,comment
John,"He said ""Hello"""
```
✓ Correctly converts to: He said "Hello"

### Empty Values
```csv
name,age
John,30
Jane,
```
Empty fields become `null`

## Testing

Run the test suite:
```bash
node csv-parser.test.js
```

Expected output:
```
🧪 Running CSV Parser Test Suite...

✓ testBasicParsing passed
✓ testQuotedFieldsWithCommas passed
... (40 tests total)

==================================================
Tests passed: 40/40
Tests failed: 0/40
==================================================

🎉 All tests passed!
```

## API Summary

```javascript
// Main function
parseCSV(input, options?) → CSVResult

// CSVResult properties
result.rows              // Array of objects
result.headers           // Array of strings
result.errors            // Array of {row, message}

// CSVResult methods
result.filter(fn)        // Returns filtered array
result.sum(column)       // Returns number
result.average(column)   // Returns number
result.count()           // Returns number
result.groupBy(column)   // Returns Map
```

## Tips & Tricks

### Chaining Operations
```javascript
// Filter then sum
const engineerSalaries = result.sum(
  result.filter(e => e.dept === 'Engineering')
);
// Note: filter returns array, not CSVResult
// So you'd need to do this differently:

const engineers = result.filter(e => e.dept === 'Engineering');
const totalSalary = engineers.reduce((s, e) => s + e.salary, 0);
```

### Working with Grouped Data
```javascript
const grouped = result.groupBy('region');

// Iterate groups
for (const [region, sales] of grouped) {
  const total = sales.reduce((s, r) => s + r.amount, 0);
  console.log(`${region}: $${total}`);
}

// Get specific group
const northSales = grouped.get('North');
```

### Complex Analysis
```javascript
const data = parseCSV(csv);

// Count with condition
const count = data.filter(row => row.status === 'active').length;

// Multiple groupings
const primary = data.groupBy('category');
primary.forEach((rows, category) => {
  const secondary = rows.reduce((acc, row) => {
    if (!acc[row.subcategory]) acc[row.subcategory] = [];
    acc[row.subcategory].push(row);
    return acc;
  }, {});
  console.log(`${category}:`, secondary);
});
```

